    {
        "name": "Charles Conrad",
        "nationality": "American",
        "short_biography": "Elite naval aviator and aeronautical engineer who commanded Apollo 12, becoming the third human being to walk on the surface of the Moon.",
        "long_biography": "Charles 'Pete' Conrad Jr. was born on June 2, 1930, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. Overcoming severe childhood dyslexia through absolute discipline, he developed a deep fascination with mechanical design, earning a Bachelor of Science in Aeronautical Engineering from Princeton University in 1953. He entered the U.S. Navy, qualifying as an elite fighter pilot and subsequently graduating from the U.S. Naval Test Pilot School at Patuxent River, where he served as a premier flight instructor and experimental systems evaluator. NASA selected him for Astronaut Group 2 in 1962. Conrad first launched into space aboard Gemini 5 in 1965, setting a global spaceflight endurance record, and later commanded Gemini 11 in 1966, executing a direct-ascent orbital rendezvous tracking profile on his first orbit. His supreme engineering reflexes led directly to his assignment as the Commander of Apollo 12. On November 19, 1969, Conrad executed a pinpoint manual landing of the Lunar Module 'Intrepid' in the Ocean of Storms, landing within walking distance of the robotic Surveyor 3 spacecraft to retrieve its telemetry hardware. Stepping onto the lunar surface, he famously joked about his height, saying, 'Whoopie! Man, that may have been a small one for Neil, but that's a long one for me.' Over two historic extravehicular activities totaling nearly eight hours, he deployed complex scientific payloads and collected invaluable lunar core samples. Conrad later commanded Skylab 2 in 1973, leading a high-risk operational rescue mission where he performed a grueling spacewalk to manually deploy a jammed solar array, saving America's first space station from catastrophic power failure.",
        "image_url": "static/images/astronauts/pete_conrad.jpg",
        "missions": ["Gemini 5", "Gemini 11", "Apollo 12", "Skylab 2"],
        "birth_date": "1930-06-02",
    },
    {
        "name": "Alan Bean",
        "nationality": "American",
        "short_biography": "Accomplished aeronautical engineer, test pilot, and artist who served as the Lunar Module Pilot for Apollo 12, walking on the Moon.",
        "long_biography": "Alan LaVern Bean was born on March 15, 1932, in Wheeler, Texas. Showing an exceptional technical aptitude for aviation layouts and material physics, he attended the University of Texas at Austin, graduating with a Bachelor of Science in Aeronautical Engineering in 1955. He commissioned into the U.S. Navy, qualifying as an elite fighter pilot flying jet interceptors before being selected for the U.S. Naval Test Pilot School. There, he trained under Pete Conrad, evaluating experimental structural modifications and advanced electrical tracking systems on naval aircraft. NASA selected him for Astronaut Group 3 in October 1963. On November 14, 1969, Bean launched into space as the Lunar Module Pilot for Apollo 12. During the turbulent launch phase, the Saturn V rocket was struck twice by lightning, causing a catastrophic telemetry dropout that threatened to abort the mission; Bean executed a critical, highly obscure manual override switch sequence ('Set SCE to Aux') that instantly restored the spacecraft's electrical systems. On November 19, 1969, he followed Pete Conrad onto the lunar surface, spending nearly eight hours executing advanced scientific tracking operations, setting up a nuclear-powered data station, and collecting core geology components. Bean later served as Commander of Skylab 3 in 1973, logging 59 days in orbit and running massive biological payloads. Following his retirement, he channeled his unique sensory memories into a prominent career as an artist, utilizing real lunar dust and spacecraft foil patches to paint highly descriptive landscapes of humanity's lunar achievements.",
        "image_url": "static/images/astronauts/alan_bean.jpg",
        "missions": ["Apollo 12", "Skylab 3"],
        "birth_date": "1932-03-15",
    },
    {
        "name": "David Scott",
        "nationality": "American",
        "short_biography": "Elite military pilot and aeronautical engineer who commanded Apollo 15, becoming the seventh human to walk on the Moon and the first to drive the Lunar Rover.",
        "long_biography": "David Randolph Scott was born on June 6, 1932, in San Antonio, Texas. Raised in a disciplined military infrastructure, he attended the United States Military Academy at West Point, graduating fifth in his class in 1954. He entered the U.S. Air Force as an elite fighter pilot before pursuing graduate research at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), where he earned both a Master of Science in Aeronautics/Astronautics and an Engineer in Aeronautics/Astronautics degree in 1962, specializing in automated orbital tracking and guidance software. NASA selected him in 1963 for Astronaut Group 3. Scott first flew into orbit on March 16, 1966, alongside Neil Armstrong as the Pilot of Gemini 8, where he assisted in managing a near-fatal thruster spin anomaly. He later served as the Command Module Pilot for Apollo 9, executing critical structural tests of the docked Apollo spacecraft configurations in Earth orbit. Scott's deep engineering and geological tracking focus led to his selection as Commander of Apollo 15 in 1971. He manually piloted the Lunar Module 'Falcon' down to the rugged Hadley-Apennine region of the Moon. Over three historic extravehicular activities totaling 18 hours and 35 minutes, Scott became the first human to drive the Lunar Roving Vehicle, exploring complex volcanic rilles and discovering the famous 'Genesis Rock' core sample. Before ascending, he conducted a famous televised physics demonstration in the lunar vacuum, dropping a heavy geology hammer and a falcon feather simultaneously to visually confirm Galileo's gravitational laws, establishing a milestone in planetary scientific education.",
        "image_url": "static/images/astronauts/david_scott.jpg",
        "missions": ["Gemini 8", "Apollo 9", "Apollo 15"],
        "birth_date": "1932-06-06",
    },
    {
        "name": "James Irwin",
        "nationality": "American",
        "short_biography": "Accomplished aeronautical engineer and military test pilot who served as the Lunar Module Pilot for Apollo 15, walking on the Moon.",
        "long_biography": "James Benson Irwin was born on March 17, 1930, in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. Developing an early structural focus on mechanical aerodynamics, he attended the United States Naval Academy, graduating with a Bachelor of Science in 1951, before commissioning into the U.S. Air Force. He went on to pursue advanced research at the University of Michigan, earning a Master of Science in Aeronautical Engineering and Instrumentation Engineering in 1957. Irwin built an elite military profile as an experimental test pilot, surviving a horrific aircraft crash during an instructor flight that required extensive physical reconstruction. He served as a primary tracking engineer for the development of the high-altitude Lockheed YF-12 interceptor program before NASA selected him for Astronaut Group 5 in 1966. On July 26, 1971, Irwin launched into orbit as the Lunar Module Pilot for Apollo 15. On July 30, he and David Scott executed a complex descent to the lunar surface. Over their three days in the Hadley-Apennine valley, Irwin logged over 18 hours of physical extravehicular activity, working alongside Scott to deploy advanced geological drilling instruments, map tectonic surface faults, and secure core rock layers. The intense physical exertion in the rigid spacesuit triggered a severe cardiovascular anomaly, causing Irwin to experience acute heart arrhythmias in orbit, which were actively monitored by biomedical telemetry teams via ground controls. Following his safe return, his profound experience on the lunar surface led him to resign from NASA to establish the High Flight Foundation, dedicating his remaining life to global humanitarian and spiritual outreach programs.",
        "image_url": "static/images/astronauts/james_irwin.jpg",
        "missions": ["Apollo 15"],
        "birth_date": "1930-03-17",
    },
    {
        "name": "Charles Duke",
        "nationality": "American",
        "short_biography": "Elite military pilot and test engineer who served as Lunar Module Pilot for Apollo 16, becoming the youngest human to walk on the Moon.",
        "long_biography": "Charles Moss Duke Jr. was born on October 3, 1935, in Charlotte, North Carolina. Displaying an exceptional analytical mind, he attended the United States Naval Academy, graduating with a Bachelor of Science in Naval Sciences in 1957 before commissioning into the U.S. Air Force. He went on to earn a Master of Science in Aeronautics and Astronautics from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in 1964, specializing in the guidance and control tracking interfaces of manned systems. Duke graduated from the Aerospace Research Pilot School, mastering advanced supersonic intercepts before NASA selected him for Astronaut Group 5 in 1966. He first gained global prominence during the Apollo 11 mission in 1969, serving as the official Capsule Communicator (CAPCOM) in mission control; his calm, distinctive southern voice guided Neil Armstrong down through critical computer alarms during the high-stress landing sequence. In 1972, Duke was assigned as the Lunar Module Pilot for Apollo 16. On April 21, at the age of 36, he stepped onto the Descartes highlands, making him the youngest individual in human history to walk on the Moon. Alongside John Young, Duke logged 20 hours and 14 minutes of extravehicular activity across three days, operating the Lunar Rover to collect over 210 pounds of core samples and executing unique material science tracking. Following his return, Duke utilized his technical leadership to direct corporate asset operations and international aerospace consulting frameworks across the planet.",
        "image_url": "static/images/astronauts/charles_duke.jpg",
        "missions": ["Apollo 16"],
        "birth_date": "1935-10-03",
    },
    {
        "name": "Eugene Cernan",
        "nationality": "American",
        "short_biography": "Elite naval aviator and aerospace engineer who commanded Apollo 17, leaving the final human footprints on the lunar surface.",
        "long_biography": "Eugene Andrew Cernan was born on March 14, 1934, in Chicago, Illinois. Driven by an intense structural focus on aviation physics, he attended Purdue University, graduating with a Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering in 1956, before commissioning into the U.S. Navy. He went on to earn a Master of Science in Aeronautical Engineering from the Naval Postgraduate School. As a decorated Navy fighter pilot, Cernan logged over 5,000 flight hours, mastering high-stress carrier operations before NASA selected him for Astronaut Group 3 in 1963. He first launched into orbit aboard Gemini 9A in 1966, performing a grueling, near-fatal two-hour spacewalk where inadequate tracking metrics caused his visor to fog completely, forcing an emergency manual return. He later served as Lunar Module Pilot for Apollo 10 in 1969, executing a low-altitude orbital pass just 47,000 feet above the lunar surface to track landing grids. His unmatched operational stamina led to his assignment as Commander of Apollo 17 in December 1972—the final mission of the Apollo lunar architecture. Cernan manually piloted the Lunar Module 'Challenger' down to the Taurus-Littrow valley. Over three days, he logged an unprecedented 22 hours and 4 minutes of physical surface extravehicular activity, driving the rover to collect deep core geological samples. Before ascending, Cernan etched his daughter's initials into the lunar soil and delivered an immortal closing address, leaving the final human footprints on the Moon and framing the baseline architecture for future planetary return missions.",
        "image_url": "static/images/astronauts/eugene_cernan.jpg",
        "missions": ["Gemini 9A", "Apollo 10", "Apollo 17"],
        "birth_date": "1934-03-14",
    },
    {
        "name": "Harrison Schmitt",
        "nationality": "American",
        "short_biography": "Brilliant Harvard geologist and academic who became the first professional scientist and only geologist to walk on the lunar surface during Apollo 17.",
        "long_biography": "Dr. Harrison Hagan 'Jack' Schmitt was born on July 3, 1935, in Santa Rita, New Mexico. Developing an early, intense focus on planetary structures and mineral layouts, he attended the California Institute of Technology, graduating with a Bachelor of Science in Geology in 1957. He pursued advanced academic tracks at Harvard University, earning a Ph.D. in Geology in 1964 after conducting extensive fieldwork mapping structural fault lines in Europe and Alaska. Schmitt worked for the U.S. Geological Survey's Astrogeology Branch, designing the specialized field mapping techniques and tracking matrices subsequently used by early Apollo crews. NASA selected him as part of its first group of scientist-astronauts in June 1965. To ensure he met mission piloting baselines, Schmitt spent a full year completing jet pilot training, earning his Air Force wings. On December 7, 1972, he launched aboard Apollo 17 as the Lunar Module Pilot. Walking on the Taurus-Littrow surface alongside Eugene Cernan, Schmitt brought professional geological diagnostic capability to the Moon. Over 22 hours of surface tracking, he discovered the famous 'orange soil'—a deposit of microscopic volcanic glass spheres that proved the Moon experienced ancient explosive volcanic activity. Following his return, Schmitt leveraged his technical data assets to serve as a U.S. Senator for New Mexico from 1977 to 1983 and later became a leading corporate consultant on energy infrastructures and lunar resources, advocating for the extraction of Helium-3 from the lunar regolith to fuel future fusion reactors on Earth.",
        "image_url": "static/images/astronauts/harrison_schmitt.jpg",
        "missions": ["Apollo 17"],
        "birth_date": "1935-07-03",
    },
